That doesn&#39;t work, because as defined, the task at hand __is impossible with that signature__.

Consider a `Pair&lt;String, Integer&gt;`. If you swap that, then all of a sudden it&#39;d be a `Pair&lt;Integer, String&gt;`, and things cannot magically change their type midflight, that&#39;s just not how java works. Hence, this question __cannot possibly be done__ in the way you&#39;ve set it up.

Alternatives that do work:

## Homogenous pair

Instead you can forcibly state that any pair has the property that the type of the &#39;left&#39; and the &#39;right&#39; side must be identical. That doesn&#39;t mean they both have to be, say, String - one can be String and one can be Integer, but if you do that, the pair is to be considered a `Pair&lt;Object&gt;` - i.e. a pair has just one type parameter and that reflects the thing both left and right are. In that case, swap is no problem at all, and you need to add zero casts to do it. just:

```
class Pair&lt;E&gt; {
  E left, right;

  public Pair(E left, E right) {
    this.left = left;
    this.right = right;
  }

  ...

  public void swap() {
    E tmp = left;
    left = right;
    right = tmp;
  }
}
```

and voila.

Of course, it&#39;s really bizarre to add a constraint that a pair must have homogenous types like this.

## Don&#39;t swap in place, return a new pair

When you, say, cast an integer to a double, you don&#39;t _change the variable_. Instead, the expression returns a new  value. As an example:

```
double x = 5.5;
(int) x;
```

This doesn&#39;t compile. Even if it did (say, we go with `System.out.println((int) x);`, that doesn&#39;t mean the value of x is now 5. It is still 5.5 `(int) x` __does not modify `x` in any way__ - it returns a new value. You can make your pair work the same way - `swap()` __does not__ modify the pair at all, but it does return an entirely new pair:

```
public class Pair&lt;K, T&gt; {
  private K left;
  private T right;

  public Pair&lt;T, K&gt; swapped() {
    return new Pair(right, left);
  }
}
```

SLIGHT EDIT: I renamed the method to `swapped`. Naming is tricky, and `swap` implies that the state of the pair object changes, which it does not. `swapped` far more accurately conveys the idea that it just makes a new pair.

Simple, no need for casts. Callers would have to do something with the returned value, though. This:

```
Pair&lt;String, String&gt; hi = new Pair&lt;&gt;(&quot;Hello&quot;, &quot;World&quot;);
hi.swapped();
```

does nothing at all (because `swapped()` makes a new pair and returns it - ignoring what it returns, as above, means nothing happens). They&#39;d have to write:

```
Pair&lt;String, String&gt; hi = new Pair&lt;&gt;(&quot;Hello&quot;, &quot;World&quot;);
hi = hi.swapped();
```

And that would work fine. In addition, this would fail, and that&#39;s a good thing:

```
Pair&lt;Integer, String&gt; hi = new Pair&lt;&gt;(5, &quot;Hi&quot;);
hi = hi.swapped(); // nope, fails to compile
```

That&#39;s good because _it should fail_: That code makes no sense. If you swap em around, you&#39;d have a `Pair&lt;String, Integer&gt;`, and, you can&#39;t magically change the type of a local variable just by invoking a method. You can only make a new variable. This&#39;d be fine:

```
Pair&lt;Integer, String&gt; hi = new Pair&lt;&gt;(5, &quot;Hi&quot;);
Pair&lt;String, Integer&gt; hello = hi.swapped(); // no prob!
```

## An important note

Pair is bad. It&#39;s not &#39;java like&#39;. People who write Pair classes fail to understand that java is at its core a highly nominal language: Things have names and that&#39;s good. Hence, Pair is almost never a good idea. For example, imagine this code:

```
public class University {
  /**
   * @return The student; pair.left is their name, pair.right is their student id. */
  public Pair&lt;String, Long&gt; lookupStudentByBirthDate(LocalDate date) {
     ...
  }
}
```

That&#39;s crappy code. Java is nominal: if you have a concept of &#39;a student&#39;, then __make a type called `Student` to represent it__. This is the correct way to do it:

```
public class University {
  public static record Student(String name, long id) {}

  public Student lookupByBirthDate(LocalDate birthDate) {
    ...
  }
}
```

The API is much nicer now, for many reasons:

* With `Pair&lt;String, Long&gt;` it&#39;s so difficult to know what the heck that represents, the method is pretty much forced to have an unwieldy, long name - it needs to be called `lookupStudent` so that a casual reader of this API knows what it is without having to read through all of that code (in the sense that they are no longer directly familiar with it, and __all__ programmers are on any but the most academically tiny of projects: You can&#39;t remember every nook and cranny of a larger project either even if you wrote _all_ of it yourself). Now, as it returns `Student`, it&#39;s clear from context and we no longer need to do that.
* I have a pair now. I need to look stuff up to know.. was the name &#39;left&#39; and the id &#39;right&#39; or was it the other way around?
* If you want student-specific utility you have a place for it - the `Student` class. You can&#39;t add a method to your `Pair` class that makes no sense except for students. You, of course, can and should do that if we have a dedicated `Student` class.

