answers.body_markdown:
There are no union type constraints for generics, but you can just use a wildcard:

    sealed interface Result&lt;T, E&gt; {
        &lt;U, F&gt; Result&lt;U, ?&gt; andThen(Function&lt;T, Result&lt;U, F&gt;&gt; f);
    }

    record Ok&lt;T, E&gt;(T value) implements Result&lt;T, E&gt; {
        @Override
        public &lt;U, F&gt; Result&lt;U, F&gt; andThen(Function&lt;T, Result&lt;U, F&gt;&gt; f) {
            return f.apply(value);
        }
    }

    record Err&lt;T, E&gt;(E err) implements Result&lt;T, E&gt; {
        @Override
        public &lt;U, F&gt; Result&lt;U, E&gt; andThen(Function&lt;T, Result&lt;U, F&gt;&gt; f) {
            return new Err&lt;&gt;(err);
        }
    }

Obviously you&#39;re ceding some type safety as you&#39;re losing the ability to say that the wildcard type is either `E` or `F`, but this is as close as you can easily get in Java (without recourse to creating your own union type wrapper).

