I am a high school computer science teacher, who tries to teach students the &quot;proper&quot; use of different coding structures. For example a &quot;Counted Loop&quot; structure – when it is initialized to count from 0 up to the length of an array, the loop should fully progress through its entirety. If the loop needs to be interrupted early and someone uses a “break” command to do so, I have always felt that the loop should be more “properly” written using a &quot;Conditional Loop&quot;. Here are two equivalent blocks of Java code:

**Counted Loop**:
```
int[] anArray = new int[] {5, 2, 1, 4, 8};
for (int i = 0; i &lt; anArray.length; i++) {
    if (anArray[i] == 4) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Found at index &quot; + i);
        break;
    }
}
```

**Conditional Loop**:
```
int[] anArray = new int[] {5, 2, 1, 4, 8};
int i = 0;
boolean found = false;
while (!found &amp;&amp; i &lt; anArray.length) {
    if (anArray[i] == 4) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Found at index &quot; + i);
        found = true;
    }
    i++;
}
```

The way I understand (*and justified my thinking/teaching*) is that the higher level programming languages that we use are simply our way of communicating with the computer to have it complete tasks. The compiler has to convert these higher level languages into “Assembler” or other lower level languages for the computer system to use/execute. When code is written that &quot;works&quot; but is not necessarily using the coding constructs in their intended structure, does this tend to make the compiled code less reliable, less efficient, or ultimately longer -- as it would need to add extra structures to adjust for the “misuse” of these code structures. Is this the case or will they basically do the same and it is irrelevant?

I have always felt that the first block of code above is &quot;poor&quot; coding and should properly be written in the second form. So I just wanted to know if I need to adjust my thinking and teaching and allow students to use these methods to write code.

